text: ...nope. This is what you people call 'diversity'? As a black man from another country, this is no different than any other American movie-only the skin colour of the actors is a darker tone. I have seen your home invasion movies as well as 'body swap' movies. See this is what I've been saying for years-the black people in America aren't some wildly different culture that will have a different ideas...you are ALL just AMERICAN. If you want diversity, try watching movies from DIFFERENT CULTURES, not the same culture with different melanin levels; that way you'll get new ideas, new concepts, new mythology, different values, different social interactions-hell, even different settings. At least that's how some of us in other countries see you. Case in point, this movie...it seems to be channeling its inner 'Invasion of the body snatchers'...only because it wants to be black focused it dramatically reduces the scale, which, because I know of a movie where more is at risk, makes it seem less impressive. Furthermore...you're going to need to have a DAMN good reason why this family in particular is being copied-they aren't famous nor do they look particularly filthy rich (just the regular rich white people type of rich in these movies...it makes sense, fuck off).  I would be more interested if it was a planet wide event, like the movie it's copying, or they better set up why anyone would want to copy this family.       That said the mother is hot as FUCK.

text: I just realized something.   You know how the mother in the beginning (the real one) is being rather super protective of his son? Like to the point of telling to just 'stay with him to make sure he was safe'? Now consider that the clone son (And it's obviously the rabbits are a reference to the first rabbit that was ever 'cloned' in 2002) acted animistic, like he just was simply following orders with no objections to the mother clone (similar to how there are certain families that involve children who are unusually super dependent on their families that it gets awkward).   Clones will represent the worst aspects of the family (or rather what the family wishes the other members could be and drag it up to 11) and will show extreme irony. So for example, daughter wants to become a great dancer, and clone daughter will represent those that will do whatever it takes to get that 'popularity and honor', to the point of killing others (A la black Swan).   Also, minor thing. The whole 'the song is about drugs' could be another foreshadowing to drug testing, which are mostly done on rabbits. And Jordan Peele also directed "Get Out", which involved themes of racism (and a slight amount of references to slavery). And most of the clones that were seen in 1:57 weren't Caucasian. I think he's flat out saying that animal testing is similar to torture.

text: I'm almost certain.... No, I guarantee this film is examining how they're fighting the doppelganger version of themselves that society considers Evil... Most likely its a metaphor for families in the Black Community having to resist the urge or the struggle with resisting falling into the temptation of becoming the so-called "demonic" version that *WHITE* Society will deemed unfit, unstable, unacceptable, or unsuitable for Americanized *white* Culture and Standards... Its a Black-American Family.... more BLACK... than actually AMERICAN... maybe considered TOO BLACK by some.... And a result of Isolated Toxic Tribalism in the Black Community/Black Family structure/unit.... Think of it...  It all started with a old-school "RAP" song about "Drugs" that was just suppose to be a cool song and was harmlessly & inadvertently trying to come across as "cool/hip/innocent" to this generation of young black children of THIS Generation who have no idea what that "LIFE" was about... But Black folks 35+ know and we consciously struggle with "THAT LIFE" and the temptation it brings with listening to the lyrics of old school hip hop songs that remind us of where we come from and how far we've come in spite of whatever modern injustices occurring in the Black Communities.... It's like, "Should we let them listen to it? Should we change the station? But the song is dope! But is it actually about dope?? Wait what should I do my kids are here listening to it..." Its like fighting this other evil version of themselves is a representation of there inner-struggle to fight the urge and resist there own default toxic tribalistic nature against society in 2019

text: Just want to vent on the trend, in general, of releasing trailers this far in advance. Three freaking months until release. On one hand, I understand that Christmas Day is a good day for a trailer such as this, as people are home chilling, on their laptops or phones and creating lots of buzz and it's exciting. Secondly, I understand that February may not be the best release date for a high-profile movie, and also that the later in the year a movie gets released, the better chance it stays in the minds of the Academy.                           ...That being said, I really wish that movies would limit the gap to 1 month, 6 weeks tops. The energy built up towards a film dissapates when too much time passes and people may even tire of it, yet I'm certain in this case, it won't affect this film. It's just royally annoying and frustrating. I feel the same way about political campaigns before an election. Some countries limit it to 6 months before an election, which I wished the U.S. would have. Two years of campaigning is absolutely mind-numbing, dispiriting and distracting to the proper working of a democracy.  Okay. I'm vented.

text: The Tethered are the monsters in this movie, they found a way to come to our side of the world and are trying to take over...Lupitia as a child came across them before, hence her knowing about them, look in the background of several scenes, there's bodies everywhere, that's because it's not just happening to them, it's happening to the whole town...The Tethered are killing the "real" version and Lupitia and her family are trying to find out how to stop them...this film isn't about race, but it is the first time an African American family has been featured as leads in a movie like this...it's kinda like Invasion of the Body Snatchers...it's always been a white person or their family...so Jordan Peele wanted to make a horror film where we got to see from our POV what we would do and how we would handle ourselves in this situation... we're not looking at "them" in this situation, we're looking at "us" in this situation

text: OK. So I live at the corner of Alhambra Ave & East Cliff Dr. Anyone that knows where this was shot, knows the significance of that corner. We did have to grant permission to them have this film shot there. Also, we got a little inside info AND an early screening of the film.  So, this African american family moved from a heavily populated black community, to a more "white" community. Certain bay area towns have a very high white population (SC). This is why he chose this location. Anyways, they move to this white beach town. And their white neighbors flip out. The white neighbors pretend to be democrat, loving all races. That is, Until a black family moves in next to them. And the neighbor white father works at a San Jose cloning lab. He is able to to get samples of them, DNA, picture samples of the family. And he wires the clones to have the sole enemy of "themselves". The whole point is to get the black family to move out of town. Basically, its a comment on humans. People are loving of other races, until a black family moves in next door. The message is. White people construct these social economic neighborhoods, ghettos, good neighboorhods. White people set it up, so black people fight, and kill amongst themselves. While the white families are on the good side of town, away from the violence. Its all socially constructed. Peele is a genius. This movie will be HUGE!

text: My personal thought, and I'll accept any criticism for thinking this: The Tethered are the "Real" Wilson family, meant to represent what it really means to truly be black, and to take pride in who you are and what your race is.    The Wilsons, in the film, will be revealed as clones or some such thing, made by white people to make them more acceptable to their society. The underlying metaphor and message of the movie will be about how black people are forced to cast aside their race and culture in order to appease white people and be accepted into white society, which is seen as the only way of them being able to "move up" in the world.    The Tethered is who they truly are, and will represent how The Wilsons have changed so much about themselves to meet the approval of white society, that they are strangers to who they use to be, to their former culture. It will end with them accepting their deaths, and either letting The Tethered take over their lives, showing how its important to, for lack of a better term, "stay black", and stay true to yourself and your race and culture, or it will have both The Tethered and The Wilsons dying, showing that giving up your culture in an attempt to conform to one that hateful and racist only hurts you and your people and your peoples culture in the end.    TL;DR Version: This movie WILL have a "White people/culture are/is evil" message, but it's a REALLY strong and good message that should NOT be ignored.

text: I loved Get Out because of Jordan Peele's use of symbolism and semiotics, but I fear that in this film he may of gone too far from his subtle use of animals, race and gender in Get Out. Just from the trailer, the over use of the white rabbit (which can be translated as a symbol for the love and tenderness of magical manifestations) gets me worried that he is no longer going to be giving us beautiful examples of his pure talent in film making through his diverse use of symbolism. text: Calling it now before we all see the movie this weekend: The mom, Adelaide, is the only Tethered we see who'd talked because she's the only one who can talk. Because she's NOT a tethered. She's the original. The Tethered Young Adelaide in the flashback scenes replaced her, but by replacing her, became her so completely she forgot she wasn't ever the original. Because she abandoned and forgot about the others, they accepted the real Adelaide as one of their own (and thus Tethered Adelaide is now "one of them") and so she lived with them until the movie (and possibly was part of how they are now out in force?). The whole thing is supposed to be not about race, but class  this time right? The tethered being a fairly obvious message in that light: There is somebody out there, as smart as you, as capable as you, so much like you, but things didn't go so well for them so they didn't get as far. If you neglect that truth they are gonna be mad about it. And while there are some racial parallels you can make, there's a universal class constant as well: When one of you get out, but "forgets" about "where they came from", that's the one you REALLY hate.

text: Do yourself a favor and SKIP THIS MOVIE. On the way in the theatre the manager asked me for feedback after the show (I'm there a lot so he knows me ) , he told me that he had people telling him that it wasn't very good and that a couple people had walked out of the earlier showing. I had went expecting it to be great because rotten tomatoes gave it a 95 rating,( I'm guessing that rating was politically motivated like a lot of their movie ratings are now). The first half hour was like watching paint dry, it is so slow moving you are actually sitting there for about 5 mins watching rabbits in cages ,the music and background music is terrible, about 45 mins in the middle of the movie was somewhat entertaining, not great but ok, the  last 1/2 hour is not just bad it is actually very irritating and took every bit of patience I had to sit through the last 15 mins. Just like the manager had told me about the earlier show a couple had got up and left about 3/4 of the way thru this one. When I stopped on the way out to give the manager the feedback, other people heard us talking and stopped to say they were disappointed too ,and the impressions ranged from " unbelievably bad " to " it was just ok " but everybody was expecting it to be really good and was very disappointed

text: --- Major Spoiler Alert-----This will Spoil movie - do not read  This movie is very simple actually but well done . I think that the cover of the movie basically explains everything that Peele is masterfully trying to convey. There is a picture of the mother with tears in her eyes and a mask with a smile on it on the cover of the movie. This is symbolic of the evil, sadness, concealment, boundage and struggle that lies BENEATH this country and what you see everyday; which we consider as normal life here in the U. S. . The mother crying underneath the mask is the original mother and the smiling mask being removed is the doppelganger. This picture symbolizes What Lies Beneath the smiling doppelgangers face;a man hidden, a story hidden.   1.) The movie starts off with the crime of the doppelganger STEALING BY FORCE  the life of the original young mother and putting her in bondage, in a controlled environment, unable to flourish. So throughout the movie we sympathize with the doppelganger and she actually plays the victim in the movie. The truth is, she was created unnaturally  and committed a evil violent act to exist in her present world & location.  Her existence in the family and location she STOLE came with the PRIVILEGE of existing as; wife, mother and friend.  Note: What  I mean by created  UNNATURALLY could be as simple as  being driven by an evil implanted idea (selectively replace people) , principle or upbringing.   2.) The only way the mother's (doppelgangers) life could continue as is; was to conceal the truth of her crimes at all cost to continue her life. She had to lie and actually murder all that could provide evidence of her crime. ***That is why she was the most aggressive in the entire movie(with intent and reason) and consequentially had the largest KILL COUNT and follow through  ***.   3.) In conclusion, this movie Perfectly mirrors the accounts of the first European settlers arriving here in America and killing all inhabitants, completely Conquering the continent of Africa and enslaving its people to create life "as we know it" which we consider as perfectly normal. Yes, the doppelgangers are bad, most comments believe that they represent the underclass but  I think Peele totally conveys that they are here too take all that yours and replace you. I draw this comparison  due to the fact that, in the movie, The doppelgangers were manufactured and existed for all people  in the U. S. . The only way to continue the status quo in this country and beyond is to continue to steal, conceal, replace and kill. ****  I believe that the most important part of the movie is when the doppelgangers participate in keeping a perfect Unity DESPITE their insanity, symbolically representing this unity by  holding hands at the end of the movie. I think that Peele did not make the doppelgangers kill each other in an effort to convey the message of unity amongst people with the same purpose ( thievery, concealment, lies and murder). I feel that the entire movie was solely about the mother, this storyline and the premise of this comment reigning true throughout all aspects of the movie.   4.) I believe that Peele  made it where the doppelgangers resided under ground to convey the true behavior of evil. It is generally done in secret and hides. The underground places were built and exist but only known by the ones who created them and the ones using them for evil purposes. Most people are unaware of the underground spaces.   Unfortunately, we will never know what the mothers (doppelgangers) life would be like if she did not commit this crime. Maybe her life could have been better? Definitely more people would be alive and having to lie, steal, conceal and murder her entire life wouldn't be a requirement.  Thoughts?.....

text: SPOILERS: I saw this is another comment section about this movie and thought it was pretty interesting. If you've seen the movie, you know at the end that who we thought was Adelaide was actually Red, and that Red switched places with Adelaide when they met in the tunnel. The comment explained that humans were inferior to the tethered (they gained strength from what humans couldn't do), and Adelaide (Red) became inferior after living with the humans for years. When talking about why she quit ballet, she said her legs gave out on her. When the daughter was explaining why she wanted to quit running, she said her legs were not strong enough. The guy who made the comment noted that Adelaide (Red) passed this onto her daughter, while Red (Adelaide) passed strength within legs onto her daughter, which is why the tethered version of the daughter could easily outrun her. Another comment noted how the son made a tunnel at the beach instead of a castle, didn't know what a baseball bat was, and drew a photo from the angle that the mom met the tethered in the tunnel (but the drawing was of Jason and the homeless man on the beach). It could be argued that Jason switched with the tethered son aswell, as the tethered son had weak legs and crawled for a majority of the movie. The only thing that wouldn't make sense about that last part would be if they switched places that soon, how would he have burned his face that quick and lost his ability to speak? That one might be a bit of a reach but it was pretty interesting.

text: Saw this movie last week - you go from laughter to holding your breath to hiding your face in a whole circuit of emotions. Jordan Peele really knows how to build tension, and really make the viewer feel an uncomfortable dread, while still peppering in dialogue that pokes fun at the horror genre and makes you burst out laughing. And Lupita Nyong'o was brilliant, as were the rest of the cast, but she stands out in the lead role. She commits to both characters so deeply, you almost forget that it's one actor playing two roles.  Worth seeing on the big screen. Really unique movie that leaves you feeling fulfilled, but at the same time, left with a lot of questions to mull over. I've never left a theatre after watching a horror movie, talking with my friends and other movie watchers about what they took away from it.

text: I'm bored of haunted houses/supernatural, monster, zombies and slasher horror films. They are SO repetitive. Nothing unique. Different movies using the same idea and clich√©s over and over and over, over 30+ years. Just look for the horror films of the last years.  That's why I like movies like Us. In the trailer, it looks like another home invasion film, but it's so much more than that. It's not simply a horror film. It's a movie you have to watch at least twice to fully understand the meaning and all the symbols appearing since the very beginning. And the social message is relevant, something we need to talk about as a society, especially in the USA. Plus, the performance of the actors, the music and the production were great. It's a film to make you think, to make you talk. It doesn't need to have all the answers because you HAVE to think (a huge difference with common horror movies, because usually you don't need to think to understand them; they are pretty simple). If you don't understand the movie message, I recommend you to look for it in the internet. People from the United States need to understand and think about the problem. As the Tethered introduced themselves: "We are americans".
